@jmborer Please don't change the permission (644 -> 755). Could you please add unit tests?

> I really hope this very annoying bug will be included in the 10 release.

Unfortunately, this is not a critical or blocker issue. So, I think it would be included after NetBeans 10.
@lkishalmi Can we include this in NB10?

@mkleint Could you please review this if possible?

Iâ€™ll try to extend the existing unit test, but the problem is that currently the reports path is deducted from the project context, because the surefire plugin no longer logs the path on the console (I have filed a change request for that on the surefire Jira). It is very difficult to create a unit test for this feature without a mocking framework as you see below:

```
try {
   Object defaultValue = PluginPropertyUtils.createEvaluator(visitor.getContext().getCurrentProject())
                        .evaluate("${project.build.directory}/surefire-reports");
   if (defaultValue instanceof String) {
      outputDir = (String) defaultValue;
       // don't want to create link on the surefire line
      // visitor.setOutputListener(new TestOutputListener(runningTestClass, outputDir), true);
   }
   return;
} catch (ExpressionEvaluationException ex) {
   Exceptions.printStackTrace(ex);
}
```
The PluginPropertyUtils.createEvaluator expects a NbMavenProjectImpl and it is very difficult to create a fake Maven version of it, because it is not an interface and the constructor of the class NbMavenProjectImpl or even the factory require also not easily fakables objects:

`NbMavenProjectImpl(FileObject folder, FileObject projectFO, ProjectState projectState)`

I would have loved to be able to use Mockito in this case, but because of my lack of time, I didnâ€™t have time to check if it is available and if I have the Â«Â rightÂ Â» to add such kind of stuff to the NB build system.
If the NB build would have been Maven based, this would could be done more easily, but I am not even sure this would have properly worked.

Therefore I can write a unit test that will show that the expressions work with "logging" enabled or not, but I won't be able unit test the path fallback based on the MavenProjectImpl...

If you have an idea how to Mock the project path in this context, I would really appreciate your help here.
